snippet.textDisplay:
I don't think not knowing useless facts and trivia should be considered dumb. Sure it can be fun to know the origins of certain expressions or the birth dates of some important people in history but to me intelligence is more about how you deal with new situations, how you process certain rules and apply them to examples or how quickly you can make connections and recognize patterns.
If I take two random people from medieval times and give each of them a sample of a few modern video games, the smarter one is going to finish them first, not the one who knows the etymology of every word in the English language.
snippet.textOriginal:

snippet.textDisplay:
I think it’s less being stupid and more just, assuming things. People assume things their whole lives until told otherwise. Sometimes it just, doesn’t come up. I grew up calling quesadillas “cheese tias” well into middle school, despite the fact that my mother speaks fluent Spanish. Sometimes I still call them that. It just, stuck.

it’s the human condition to go “you don’t know fact I learned years ago! Where have you been? Boy, you’re dumb.” when no one learns things at the same pace. No one has the same life.

I could point out a ladybug larvae in preschool, and knew all the stages of a butterfly. Still asked if bugs could breath in high school.

Sometimes stuff just doesn’t click.
